---- Original message ----
>Date: Wed, 12 Jun 2002 17:42:17 -0400
>From: "Michael Benthin (MUTS)" <benthin(-at-)prodigy.net>  
>Subject: [T2] Make your own pod for luggage rack  
>To: Boethian Bohemian <boethianbohemian(-at-)hotmail.com>
>Cc: type2(-at-)type2.com
>
>Re storage on luggage rack: (I can send pics to the 
dimensionally
>challenged, or ask me for the web site showing this).
>My sig shows the pod I put on my Westy- besides space for 
lots of
>decals, it holds: 1. stock VW tent minus the poles (I hang 
it under the
>awning). 2. 50 ft hank of house extension cord. 3. quickie 
tent (no
>floor) I fasten to awning when bugs are not a problem. 4. 
Folding chair
>(the collapse into a tube shape kind. 5. 10 "waffle block" 
van levelers;
>these interlock to various heights and can be used to get 
out of snow or
>sand. 6. Ground cloth tarp. 7. 1gall. spare gas can. 8. 
water jug
>(minute made 3 qt OJ jug). 9. 4" length of 3" dryer vent, 
aluminum (for
>running bus in place to make power and divering exhaust 
away). 10. flat
>box to hold tent pegs, hammer, rope, spring clamps, etc.
>   The pod is made as follows: the base is made from 
1.5x .75" "  wood
>stock that has plywood paneling stapled to the bottom. It 
forms a
>rectangle that fits into the luggage rack bottom.  You can 
cord it in
>place, but since I had 2 eyebolts sticking up already for a 
spare tire,
>I cut slots in the bottom so the eyebolts poked through; 
using 4x4"
>electrical box covers, I cut slots in them to fit over the 
eyebolts. 
>Wedges go through the eyebolts to keep the box in place. 
With the pod
>locked, no one can pull it away.
>     The pod shape is made by nailing/stapling masonite to 
the box base
>on one side, and then bending it to form a half-round shape 
that is then
>fastened to the other side of the base.  Lay this agains so 
paneling and
>trace the INSIDE shape of the bend with pencil. (If you are 
too big,
>send a kid in to do this).  Cut out 2 doors this way.  
Fasten them with
>piano hinges to the bottom frame.
>At the top, for "stopping" the doors, I traced part of the 
curve onto
>some 2x4 stock and cut it out.  Glue it in place; add 
screws from the
>outside to keep it there.   Get cabinet locks and use these 
to lock the
>end doors.  Paint the masonit throuroughly; remember it is 
made from
>"paper" but as a curved arch, you can sit or stand on the 
box.  My
>milage did not go down with this on top.  It is light 
enough for one
>person to remove it.  For access, stand on the heel arch 
(door open) or
>make a ladder as I did using a boat ladder hung from u 
shapes I bend
>from aluminum stock that is bolted to the bottom of the 
driver side trip
>that matches the sliding door track arch.  A bungee clips 
it to fender.
